Söder comments on the Corona layer after mass infection
Munich - Health Minister Melanie Huml (CSU) has already announced a test offensive for large farms on Sunday.
The press conference will be shown live on our homepage.
The case in Mamming in the district of Dingolfing-Landau has startled authorities and politicians.
Almost 500 harvesters from several countries are currently working on the large vegetable farm, and more than a third have become infected with the Corona pathogen.
The farm is now under quarantine and is closed with a building fence.
No one is allowed to leave the grounds, food is delivered.
The authorities now offer free Corona tests to the 3,300 residents of the municipality.
Since the harvesters had little contact with the local population, the district office has so far assumed that the infections have not spread beyond the farm.
"remorse": confession of the alleged arsonist of Nantes
"My client was cooperative," lawyer Quentin Chabert told the newspaper.
The defender added, "He greatly regrets the deeds, the confession was a liberation for him."
His mandate was "plagued by remorse and greatly taken away by the extent of the destruction".
In the event of a conviction, the man is threatened with ten years imprisonment and a fine of 150,000 euros.
The Gothic St. Peter and Paul Cathedral in Nantes was severely damaged in a fire last week on Saturday night.
The fire broke out in three distant places in the church.
Laboratory tests confirmed the suspicion of arson.
The suspect was arrested a few hours after the fire.
He was released after a day.
The man works as a volunteer for the diocese of Nantes and was responsible for the closure of the cathedral on the eve of the fire.
Since there was no trace of a violent penetration into the church, he quickly came into the sight of the investigators.
Discuss the abolition of the 50 + 1 rule
Former DFB President Reinhard Grindel has recommended thinking about abolishing the 50 + 1 rule.
"German football should at least discuss setting conditions and clear rules for investors before the EU Commission creates fait accompli," said Grindel of Bild am Sonntag.
He stressed: "For the clubs that are most likely to become dangerous in Bavaria and Dortmund, the 50 + 1 rules do not work anyway: see Leipzig or Leverkusen.
In this respect, one cannot avoid the debate as to whether it is not necessary to facilitate the involvement of investors for clubs that want to break into this phalanx. "
However, he has doubts as to whether there is a willingness in the German Football League to allow majority shareholdings, which are prohibited in the Bundesliga by the 50 + 1 rule.
"It remains a legal risk to draw investment fences around Bundesliga as a business location in a European internal market," said Grindel.
The former DFB boss sees the danger that "the attempts to ensure a more competitive balance in the Bundesliga only weaken the competitiveness of our top clubs at European level in the end, but do not lead to more tension in the championship".
Even an equal distribution of TV money would not achieve a decisive effect.
"FC Bayern generates sales of 750 million euros, Borussia Dortmund of 500 million and RB Leipzig of 300 million.
So the differences are immense among the first three clubs alone.
The other 15 clubs have an average budget of 130 million, "said the 58-year-old.
With a view to the past, Grindel feels betrayed.
"Unfortunately, there were people who noticed this mistake and stabbed the press instead of addressing it," said Grindel about accepting an expensive watch that led to his resignation in April 2019.
"That occupied me very much humanly".
He had received the gift worth around 11,000 euros from a Ukrainian official.
"I committed a compliance violation, and it was right to draw the consequences from it," said Grindel.
"I handled the ominous watch gift in a completely transparent and unsuspecting way.
Many in the DFB knew about it. "
He never "made a secret of the gift," assured the 58-year-old.
"This may be called naive, at least this form of transparency was the complete opposite of corruption."
"Black Lives Matter": injured and one dead
The protests against police violence in the United States have escalated again through Donald Trump's use of federal police in several cities.
On Saturday, there were clashes between protesters and police officers in various cities.
Three people were injured in Louisville and 16 arrested in Seattle.
In Austin, a person was killed by shots while a demonstration march was crossing a crossroads.
Previously, there had been clashes again in Portland during protests against racism and police violence.
The security forces, including federal police officers, used tear gas on the night of Saturday and forcibly dispersed demonstrators.
Hundreds, some armed protesters marched through Louisville, Kentucky on Saturday, demanding that those responsible for Breonna Taylor's death be held accountable.
The 26-year-old student was shot in March during a drug raid at her Louisville apartment.
The aim of the raid was someone else who did not live there, and no drugs were found.
On Saturday, when a member of a group called the Black American Armed Alliance fired a shot, three people were injured.
According to NBC, they were taken to the hospital.
None of them were in mortal danger.
The police set up barricades because counter-demonstrators of a white militia had also formed.
The two groups ultimately did not meet.
In Austin, Texas, a person was shot and died during a "Black Lives Matter" demonstration.
The police claimed to have detained a suspect.
She has not yet given any further information on the circumstances of the act.
Mayor Steve Adler told the New York Times that, like many in the city, he was "inconsolable and stunned" because of what had happened.
Demonstrators also clashed with the police in the American metropolis of Seattle on Saturday.
They set fire to construction vehicles in front of a youth prison, the police used glare grenades and pepper spray.
According to the Seattle Times, 16 people were arrested for resistance to police or assault.
A courthouse was set on fire in the city of Oakland, California.
A small group of demonstrators hit windows, shot down fireworks and blinded police officers with lasers, the Oakland police said on late Saturday evening (local time).
The fire was quickly extinguished.
In Aurora, a suburb of Denver, Colorado, a car drove through a crowd demonstrating on a highway.
According to the police, one of the protesters fired a gun and at least one person was taken to the hospital injured.
In addition, windows were also hit in a court and a fire was set, as the police reported.
Investigations were started.
Rakoczy in Bad Kissingen: Historical costumes defy Corona
Although the big party was missing in the spa town, visitors and actors enjoyed the Rakoczy flair of the alternative program.
It was unusual for visitors, performers and organizers: the Rakoczy weekend without Rakoczy festival.
But even if the big party mile in the city center was missing, the crowds and program highlights such as Saale, Rakoczy-Ball or Festzug, many got their money's worth with the Corona-compliant alternative program.
"I think we have managed to spread Rakoczy flair," says spa director Sylvie Thormann.
The guests would have accepted it well.
In principle, one returns to the beginnings of the Rakoczy Festival, as well as the historical ones alone were the focus of the festival.
A pleasant atmosphere
Vesna Konhäuser has been visiting Bad Kissingen with her husband for more than 25 years.
So also this time in the Corona year.
The couple have made themselves comfortable at Luitpold Casino, watching the histories strolling and listening to Cuban live music at the casino restaurant.
"I also find it so pleasant," says Konhäuser.
She does not miss the crowds that otherwise belong to Rakoczy.
But it lacks the usual program highlights, especially Saale burns on Friday evening as well as the historic procession and the final fireworks on Sunday evening.
"That's a pity.
The weather would have been great this year, "she says.
Rakoczy riding tournament to take place again
For the performers of the historical spa guests, the alternative program sometimes meant more work.
For example, for Christina Gold, who participates in the procession in a normal year and can be seen there on the carriage of the Kurgarten café.
This year she was on Saturdays and Sundays in costume on foot in the city.
"It's more strenuous, otherwise we'll have it easier," she says.
The equestrian club had less to do, even if individual riders were on the road in the park.
"We very much hope that the equestrian quadrille will take place again next year," says Chairman Ulrike Waldhofen.
She announced that after a break of several years 2021, a Rakoczy equestrian tournament would take place again.
28 Corona cases at Spanish second division club Fuenlabrada
The Spanish second division football player CF Fuenlabrada is sliding deeper and deeper into the crisis due to a Corona outbreak.
Since the newcomer from the vicinity of Madrid flew to the city of A Coruña on 20 July despite the first Corona falls, one low follows the next.
By Sunday, 28 players or team members had been tested positive, one came to the hospital, as the club announced.
Fuenlabrada from the city of the same name southwest of Madrid had the chance to reach the promotion playoffs.
Now even the relegation to the B group of the Second League threatens.
The match against Deportivo La Coruña last Monday was cancelled at the last moment, the prosecution investigated for a possible offense against public health, the Supreme Sports Authority CSD is considering the forced relegation of the club.
Players and other team members are quarantined in a hotel.
"Until the sixth day of quarantine, they did not receive a fresh towel and gel," wrote the sports newspaper "AS".
On photos you can see how players hung underwear and club clothes in their rooms in the hotel to dry, after they had to wash them themselves.
The bed linen was also not changed for five days.
Another problem is eating.
It was neither good nor sufficient, wrote "AS".
The club management, on the other hand, said that they were satisfied with the hotel.
The club's lawyer, Javier Tebas Llanas, rejected the charge of deliberately endangering public health.
The son of the president of the Spanish Primera Division, Javier Tebas, stressed that the news agency Europa Press and the sports newspaper "Marca" reported that no violations of the Corona rules established by the Football Association had been violated.
Before departure, there were four infected people until 19 July, all of whom were isolated and did not travel.
Directly before the flight to A Coruña on Monday, all players and team members were tested again.
When the team was already in A Coruña, "five or six" other team members of the Corona test were positive.
The game was cancelled 60 minutes before the kick-off, said Tebas Llanas.
