professional cyclist Tony Martin: career continuation imaginable
Time trial specialist Tony Martin is thinking about continuing his career.
Frankfurt / Main - The seven-time time-trial world champion Tony Martin can imagine continuing his cycling career.
"I am currently working with the team to define the framework conditions for how and in what form it could continue," said the 35-year-old of the "Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung".
Martin is currently employed by the Dutch team Jumbo-Visma and had considered ending his career after this year before the Corona break.
Negotiations with his team were also about the number of race days, he said.
Or other problems that would plague him as a family father, Martin said.
He used to get up after a fall, and the first thought was: "Quickly back on the bike.
Today I think as the father of a small daughter: What if ".
The professional cyclist admitted that there are certainly aspects with which he is increasingly struggling.
"But it was good for me to notice from the Corona time what I have in cycling and how much fun I enjoy it".
The time trial specialist returns to the competition at the Tour de l'Ain (5 to 9 August).
Bavaria: At least four dead on Bavaria's streets on weekends
The beautiful weather attracts bikers to the streets in many places.
For at least three people, the tour by motorcycle ends fatally.
An 18-year-old pedestrian also dies.
Schönthal - In accidents on Bavaria's streets, several, mostly young people, died on the weekend.
An 18-year-old motorcyclist was caught on Saturday near Schönthal (district of Cham) by a car that came on the countertrack.
It was initially unclear why the car came on the counter lane.
In Upper Bavaria, a 22-year-old collided on his machine with a horse-drawn carriage on Saturday.
According to the police, he was downhill at Beilngries.
In a left turn he collided with the carriage.
His injuries were so severe that he died at the scene of the accident.
Of the twelve inmates in the carriage, one man was seriously injured and one man slightly injured, the police reported.
In another fatal accident, an 18-year-old died in Bad Kötzting in the Upper Palatinate.
He had laid down on a street on the night of Sunday and was overrun by a 42-year-old driver.
According to the police, the 18-year-old wanted to sleep.
The driver could not brake in time.
At Schönberg (district of Freyung-Grafenau), a 57-year-old biker hit a car in a right turn despite emergency braking.
He died at the scene of the accident.
The 57-year-old driver suffered a shock, the remaining three people in the car remained uninjured.
The safety of motorcyclists was discussed on Saturday by Bavaria's Transport Minister Kerstin Schreyer (CSU).
In a letter to the organizer of the biker protests against driving bans announced for August, Gabor Kovacs, the minister referred to extensive investments such as underride protection on guardrails and the defusing of dangerous corners.
"We have achieved a lot for the safety of motorcyclists in recent years," the letter said.
"The number of motorized two-wheelers killed decreased by around 28 percent compared to 2011."
