Argentina rejects creditors' counter-offer
The new demands could not be met, the Ministry of Economy in Buenos Aires said on Saturday.
"That would not only be irresponsible, but also unjust," said a statement.
"While 50 percent of children in Argentina live in poverty, we cannot increase the short-term profits of our creditors."
The debt of the second largest economy in South America is no longer viable on current terms.
This is why Argentina is asking its private creditors to dispense with some of their claims of around 66 billion US dollars (around 59 billion euros).
If no agreement is reached, the country is once again threatened with bankruptcy.
It would be the ninth default in Argentine history.
Most recently, lenders had demanded higher interest rates on government bonds and changes to some contractual clauses.
However, the Argentine government is sticking to its last offer and is not willing to make any further concessions.
Argentina is in a severe financial and economic crisis.
The inflation rate recently exceeded 50 percent.
For the current year, experts expect economic power to decline by around ten percent.
At the end of May, Argentina had not paid interest claims of US $503 million and had thus slipped into a limited default.
Arriving professionally - not yet private
Dr. Stefanie Kramer concludes after her first days at the notary's office in Eggenfelden.
In the end, everything went very fast: In mid-May, Dr. Stefanie Kramer learned that she would succeed Lutz Feller in the Eggenfelden notary's office.
Only six weeks later, at the beginning of July, the lawyer with a doctorate took up the work, the normal daily business has long been running at full speed.
"But I still have to arrive privately," she explains in an interview with the Rottaler Anzeiger and laughs.
Of course, the short lead time was not enough to move the center of life from Regensburg completely to Eggenfelden, reports the native Dingolfingerin.
She is currently looking for a suitable apartment or house in the city with her husband, who works as a judge at the district court in Regensburg.
At least her husband was still able to apply for parental leave at short notice in order to ensure the care of the two daughters (3 ½ and 1 ½ years old).
In order not to have to commute every day from Regensburg, she also has an overnight stay with her parents in Dingolfing, explains the 39-year-old.
Growing up in the neighbouring region, the town of Eggenfelden has of course long been known to her.
During visits on site with her family in recent months, she found out again: "Eggenfelden is a really beautiful small town".
She was all the more pleased that she had made the race in the selection process for the vacancy.
Her native Lower Bavaria also plays a central role in Dr. Stefanie Kramer's professional career: After studying law in Passau, she completed her legal traineeship and the 2nd state examination in Regensburg.
After several positions as a notary assessor, among others in Rehau and Hof in Upper Franconia, Babenhausen in the Unterallgäu and Regensburg - during this time she also "incidentally" shouldered the doctorate in labour law - she took her first position as a notary in Rotthalmünster in the district of Passau in 2012.
In 2016, she went on parental leave, followed by the move to Regensburg.
Since then, she has served in various notaries.
When the job in Eggenfelden was advertised because of the approaching retirement of Lutz Feller, she saw the right time for full career reentry, explains the 39-year-old.
The team of their predecessor, who will take over the holiday representation in the notary's office in the future, has taken over Dr. Stefanie Kramer completely - and immediately has a praise for the team of the law firm ready: "It is going super well!"
The fact that she can rely on well-coordinated processes makes it easier for her to take care of the forthcoming relocation of the private centre of life.
In terms of kindergarten or crib places, she has already made contact with a local institution.
And if everything works as desired, she hopes to pursue her hobby soon - and get to know the most beautiful jogging routes of the Rottal.
BVB plans to start the league with a maximum of 15,000 spectators
Dortmund The largest German football stadium in Dortmund will not even be filled by 20 percent at the start of the season in the event of a fan return.
"Due to the distance control, which is mandatory, we are currently planning with 12,000 to 15,000 spectators," said Borussia Dortmund's managing director Carsten Cramer to the "Tagesspiegel".
Normally, the arena in the district city holds just over 81,000 spectators at Bundesliga matches.
In the ghost games caused by the Corona pandemic last season, the BVB lost around four million euros per game.
The Cramer, who is responsible for marketing, digitization and internationalization at BVB, hopes that, in addition to the normal spectator seats, some of the approximately 4,000 seats in the hospitality sector can also be opened again: "It is, of course, a blow to the office if these revenues completely break away".
In view of the ongoing Corona crisis, everyone is currently "well advised to take a stable page length".
"If many companies are not doing well and 6.8 million people in Germany alone are in short-time work, then the need for entertainment is limited," explained Cramer.
The Dortmund marketing boss praised the BVB professionals for their salary partial abandonment, which is intended to help overcome the crisis: "Of course, the players know that their salary waiver has a different effect than when we put 100 people who work in merchandising on short-time work".
Tiny wonders: Early start into life with a few hundred grams
Hardly heavier than a packerl of butter, just three tablespoons of blood in his entire body: that was Gabriel when he was born - he weighed exactly 273 grams.
The boy is one of about 400 premature babies who are cared for annually at the Graz Children's Clinic.
A quarter of them weigh less than 1,500 grams, a few - like Gabriel and his brothers Raphael and Michael - are extreme lightweight with less than a kilogram of birth weight.
They are so small and born so early that neither lungs, nor intestines, nor muscles are fully developed.
Their skin is sometimes so delicate that they could hurt the electrodes of an ECG.
And they are so tiny that they sometimes wear doll clothing and specially made mini diapers for them.
But not so small that they are not in voice - "and how", smiles Berndt Urlesberger.
"Even if of course they don't scream as loud as big babies".
When the whiteboard becomes a stage
Despite Corona Theater in the classroom: The whiteboard as a stage experienced the 9th grade of the St. James Gymnasium in Abtsgmünd shortly before the start of the holiday.
Actress Julia Sylvester from the Theater der Stadt Aalen presented the production "Das Heimatkleid" to the students - via video.
Afterwards, the students were able to exchange views with the actress and the director Winfried Tobias about the play and the performance via Skype.
The idea for the performance format from the current corona situation was born.
Teacher Teresa Nar was happy about the enrichment of the lessons.
Even though everyone involved agreed at the end that the direct encounter in the theatre and stage space would offer additional stimuli, the theater also sees the potential for contact with the schools.
"If we further improve the technical framework, this could be an interesting addition to the game," emphasised director Winfried Tobias.
