"Gone with the wind": film legend Olivia de Havilland is dead
Film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland is dead.
She died a natural death on Sunday in Paris at the age of 104, confirmed her spokeswoman of the German Press Agency.
de Havilland was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the Southern epic "Gone with the Wind" (1939).
Born to British parents in Tokyo, Olivia de Havilland moved to California as a toddler.
The Austrian theatre man Max Reinhardt discovered the 19-year-old in the role of Hermia von Shakespeare's "Midsummer Night's Dream".
The film studio Warner Brothers signed her for seven years and brought her out big at the side of Eroll Flynn.
She made eight films with the heartbreaker.
In 1946 she won her first Oscar in the lead role of "To Each His Own".
The film was screened in Germany under the title "Mutterherz".
Three years later, the award for best actress came in William Wyler's "The Heiress".
She was also recognized as a neurotic eccentric in "The Dark Mirror" and "The Snake's Den".
Daphne du Maurier suggested it in 1952 for the lead role in the film adaptation of her novel "My Cousin Rachel".
The play was a worldwide success.
With her longtime friend Bette Davis she played in "Wiegenlied für eine Leiche".
His marriage to the writer Marcus Goodrich (1946 – 1953) produced his son Benjamin.
In Paris, de Havilland married journalist Pierre Paul Galante and had his daughter Gisèle with him.
This marriage also broke up.
Rumors of an affair with former British Prime Minister Edward Heath have never been confirmed.
"Road to Timmendorf": Beach volleyball: Thole / Wickler miss final at comeback
Julius Thole and Clemens Wickler missed the final of the beach volleyball tournament "Road to Timmendorf".
At the meeting of the top teams in Düsseldorf they lost in the semi-finals to their national team colleagues Nils Ehlers and Lars Flüggen with 1: 2 (17: 21, 21: 17, 19: 21).
Thole / Wickler last played at the World Tour Final in Rome last September.
