In addition to the show tournament, three starting places for the German championships were played at the beginning of September in Timmendorfer Strand: The tickets were secured by Armin Dollinger / Simon Kulzer, Manuel Harms / Richard Peemüller and Simon Pfretschner / Milan Sievers.
Kalbitz ejection from AfD confirmed - FDP speaks of "fig leaf"
The exclusion of Andreas Kalbitz from the AfD is from the point of view of the FDP only a "fig leaf" and does not change the character of the party.
"The AfD is the parliamentary arm of the right-wing extremists in Germany.
Andreas Kalbitz is only part of the tip of the iceberg of the radicals in the AfD, "said FDP politician Benjamin Strasser to the news agency dpa in Berlin.
The Federal Arbitration Court of the AfD had confirmed on Saturday in Stuttgart after several hours of trial the exclusion of Kalbitz, which the majority of the Federal Executive Board had decided in May.
Kalbitz is chairman of the AfD parliamentary group in the Brandenburg Landtag.
"If the AfD really wanted to systematically remove right-wing extremists from its party, functionaries such as Björn Höcke and his supporters would have been excluded long ago," said Strasser.
"However, there is no political will for this in the AfD, because right-wing extremism is now part of the party."
CSU General Secretary Markus Blume said similarly: "The fact that Andreas Kalbitz is now excluded says nothing and does not change anything," he told the "Welt am Sonntag".
"It speaks rather volumes, how many frenetic supporters a right-wing extremist still has in the middle of the AfD".
Blume assumes that the AfD will land below five percent again in elections in the future.
"The days of the AfD in the parliaments are numbered".
Kalbitz was one of the spokesmen of the officially dissolved "wing" around the Thuringian AfD state and group chairman Björn Höcke; the Verfassungsschutz classifies the coronation as "secured right-wing extremist aspiration".
In May, the AfD federal executive committee threw Kalbitz out of the party.
As a reason, he stated that Kalbitz had not indicated an earlier membership in the now forbidden far-right "Heimattreuen Deutschen Jugend" (HDJ) and among the Republicans.
Kalbitz denies membership in the HDJ.
The chairman of the left faction in the Brandenburg Landtag, Sebastian Walter, also stressed that the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court did not change the character of the AfD: "The wolf has only eaten chalk.
The AfD remains a far-right party, whether with or without Kalbitz ".
Neither the federal party nor the right wing would be weakened with this decision.
"The manoeuvre of the Meuthen-troop is transparent.
One wants to avoid further observation by the Verfassungsschutz and tries to get through under the radar, "said Walter.
"The AfD will not get rid of the spirits it called.
A knockout does not change anything, "commented SPD General Secretary Erik Stohn on the decision in the Kalbitz case.
"Here the AfD state association and the faction held to this day as their right-wing leader".
The legal dispute over Kalbitz's membership in the AfD will continue.
He announced on Saturday that he would take civil action against the decision of the Federal Arbitration Court.
North Sea wind farms provide a good 21 percent more electricity
In the first six months of the year, the wind power plants on the German North Sea fed 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity into the grid.
This is a good 21 percent more than in the same period last year, according to the network operator Tennet in Bayreuth.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of the North Sea electricity to the mainland and the transmission through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of Tennet's grid area, have fed in a further 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
Overall, wind power from the North and Baltic Seas will reach 13.73 TWh, compared to a good 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The wind harvest at sea thus accounts for almost 19 percent of the total wind current in Germany; that is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms ensure higher generation capacities
In addition to the wind conditions, the increased contribution of offshore wind energy results from higher generation capacities, because new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past twelve months.
If the 1270 wind power plants in the North Sea were all running at full speed at the same time, they could generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
According to Tennet, the transmission capacity is 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it is expected to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we are investing 20 billion euros in the expansion of offshore grid connections," said Tennet Managing Director Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, wind farms cannot exploit their capacity at sea, but reach around 40 percent.
The record day so far this year is January 2, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce around 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, which corresponds to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could supply almost seven million households with electricity.
