Freital: Windbergfest cancelled due to Corona
The Windberg Festival does not take place this year.
The city of Freital cancelled the three-day festival planned in September.
In other years, more than 30,000 people had visited this city festival.
"We really did not make this decision easy and - aware of how difficult it is for the participants economically - we hoped until the last minute," explained Lord Mayor Uwe Rumberg (non-party).
"But ultimately we are responsible for the health of many thousands of people."
If tens of thousands had flowed into the festival grounds and into the marquee, minimum distances, hygiene regulations and contact tracking could not have been complied with in accordance with the current Corona Protection Regulation.
Or the restrictions would have been so strong that there would not have been much left of a folk festival.
Moreover, the effort to organise and monitor would increase disproportionately many times over.
Rumberg consoled for next year.
Then the city of Freital celebrates its 100th anniversary with the Winterberg Festival from 7 to 9 May 2021 and the Day of Saxony from 10 to 12 September 2021.
Dressage Olympic champion Werth in Achleiten not to beat
Achleiten - The six-time Olympic champion Isabell Werth was the outstanding rider at the dressage tournament in Achleiten, Austria.
The 51-year-old from Rheinberg came to four victories at four starts on the weekend.
After winning a Grand Prix with Weihegold and Quantaz at the start, she was unbeatable on Sunday in the Grand Prix Special and in the freestyle.
On the 15-year-old mare Weihegold Werth prevailed on Sunday in the special against the Austrian Victoria Max-Theurer on Abegglen.
Also in the freestyle the German was on Saturday on Quantaz clearly in front of her 34 year old student Victoria Max-Theurer.
Werth's winning horse Quantaz belongs to Max-Theurer.
The most successful dressage rider in the world is to establish the ten-year-old stallion in the Grand Prix.
For Quantaz it was the first freestyle ever.
Already at the first tournament in Achleiten three weeks ago Werth had won all important four tests.
The last of the three international tournaments is scheduled for 14 to 16 August.
More air traffic controllers in Worms
Worms University continues into the air: DFS Deutsche Flugsicherung endows a professorship for "Air Traffic Management".
A corresponding contract between the university and DFS has now been signed in Worms.
The contract was initially concluded for three years and will start in 2021.
With the professorship, it is possible to start studying not only in the summer semester, but also in the winter semester.
This means that twice as many students can be trained as before.
At the same time, the capacities in the university as well as at the DFS air traffic control academy are utilized evenly.
DFS will advise the university on the establishment and appointment of the professorship.
Represented at the university since 2019
Since the summer semester 2019, the first students are in the course of study Air Traffic Management as part of their training as air traffic controllers at Worms University of Applied Sciences.
This year, nine students started.
So far, the experiences of DFS are very positive, the achievements of the students are excellent.
The combination of study and pilot training makes a significant contribution to further increasing the attractiveness of the pilot profession.
"In these times, funding is not easy for us economically.
However, we firmly expect air traffic to recover and grow again in the long term.
In order to be able to fulfil our legal mandate in the future, we need highly qualified personnel, "says Professor Klaus-Dieter Scheurle, Chairman Managing Director of DFS at the signing of the contract.
"For DFS, the endowed professorship is a future-proof investment that will provide air traffic controllers with a broad, interdisciplinary knowledge base in the long term.
We are therefore continuing our good cooperation with the university and at the same time underpinning our attractiveness as an employer. "
This is also underlined by Professor Dr. Jens Hermsdorf, President of Worms University of Applied Sciences: "The endowed professorship forms an important bridge between science and industry.
With it, we would like to build on the existing cooperation with DFS Deutsche Flugsicherung as a practical partner for the dual bachelor's degree programme in Air Traffic Management. "
The trust of the German air traffic control system is both a motivation and an obligation for the Worms University of Applied Sciences to further expand its teaching and research competence in the future fields of aviation.
In use for the air traffic controllers of tomorrow, the university could set very special highlights and innovative focuses for its students with the first endowed professorship for a dual course of study.
Dr. Denis Alt, State Secretary at the Ministry of Science, Continuing Education and Culture, emphasises: "Worms University of Applied Sciences has a unique selling point in Rhineland-Palatinate with its focus on aviation.
Today's signing of the cooperation agreement strengthens the profile of the university ".
Rescue screwdriver lands on the A 45
The A 45 motorway was fully closed for about 30 minutes on Saturday afternoon towards Aschaffenburg, as the rescue helicopter was in use after a traffic accident.
A 76-year-old drove straight with a Ford at around 12.40 o'clock in the exit Alzenau-Mitte in the bend and landed at the guardrail.
Due to the impact, the front airbags triggered, the driver suffered minor injuries on the face and had to be taken to a hospital for treatment.
The injuries of the 72-year-old passenger were cared for by the emergency doctor and the patient was then flown to a hospital with the rescue helicopter.
At present, however, the police assume that there is no danger of death.
The damaged vehicle, which suffered damage of about 2000 euros, had to be towed away.
Heil wants to check other industries according to meat industry
The Corona crisis brought the conditions in parts of the meat industry to light again.
Tightening of the law is imminent.
But are they right - and will it stick to it?
Federal Minister of Labour Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to check other sectors according to the now planned strict regulations against grievances in the meat industry.
"We will look at industry by industry and then take suitable measures for the respective industry if necessary," Heil told the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against generally restricting contracts for works.
After the mass outbreak of Corona by the meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet wants to pass a law of salvation this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to employ external personnel in slaughter, dismantling and meat processing.
For this purpose, the use of work contract and temporary workers is to be banned there.
Employer President Ingo Kramer told the dpa: "Get away from a general restriction of employment contracts and temporary employment if you don't want to strangle the economy completely".
Work contracts are, for example, the basis for their added value at the customer for large areas of crafts, the construction industry and plant construction.
"The failures of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument".
Heil assured: "My goal is not to ban contracts for works everywhere in the German economy."
Work contracts make sense.
"When an industrial company orders a craftsman to install a safety system, it is a normal work contract."
The German meat industry considers a ban on contracts and temporary agency work to be unconstitutional in its industry alone.
It cannot be explained why portioning and packaging cheese should be subject to different labour law in the future than sausage, according to a statement on the bill, as the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday) reports.
In the case of a ban, the consumer price would rise by 10 to 20 percent per kilo per product.
Many Eastern European employees from contracting companies worked in the industry 16 hours a day according to the results of an examination by the NRW Occupational Safety and Health Administration.
Often they had no break.
Wage was withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also noted that the situation in the accommodation of employees was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively sharp law had already entered into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, these were bypassed by "tricky constructions".
"Now it is necessary to clean up fundamentally".
The politician announced: "In the Occupational Safety and Health Act, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, there are also measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher test rates for occupational safety and health or clear criteria for community accommodation".
The draft submitted to dpa includes amendments to the Law on the Protection of Workers' Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Minister of Consumer Protection, Ursula Nonnemacher (Green Party), considers more intensive controls necessary.
"I would like us to be able to carry out even more controls in many supervisory areas: food inspections, animal welfare, everything possible, including animal transport, for example," said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB programme "Brandenburg aktuell".
But more staff positions are also needed for more controls.
