Turin - After a redeeming goal by Cristiano Ronaldo, record champion Juventus has secured the Italian championship for the ninth time in a row.
The team around the five-time world football player made the 36th Scudetto of the club's history perfect with a 2-0 (1-0) on Sunday evening in the home game against Sampdoria Genoa.
Ronaldo scored 1-0 ahead of half.
With 83 points, Turin, which competed without the last long-injured former international Sami Khedira, is not to be displaced from first place two matchdays before the end of the season of Serie A.
Inter Milan finished seventh in the standings.
Juventus was harmless despite optical superiority in the first half, then Ronaldo hit with the last action after a free kick variant.
The 35-year-old used Miralem Pjanic directly from the penalty area border with a flat shot (45 + 7).
Ronaldo was also involved in the 2-0 against the now more offensive guests, after his shot Federico Bernardeschi dusted (67th) off.
This ensured the lackluster but decisive success.
The foulelfmeter shot at the bar in the 89th minute should have hurt only Ronaldo himself with a view to the goalscorer classification.
"It's complicated to stay mentally and physically at ball level for 90 minutes.
The games are strange, and momentum is changing very easily, "said coach Maurizio Sarri after a 2-1 win at Udinese Calcio on Thursday.
Especially the mental exhaustion of his players is great, said the Juve coach.
Because of the defeat, the Turin team had not yet been able to make the championship perfect.
In the end, Juve was reassuring at the top of the standings, mainly due to the weakness of the competitors.
In the eleven games before the match on Sunday, the Sarri-Mannschaft had only managed five victories.
It is questionable whether Ronaldo will also become the top scorer.
While the Portuguese superstar has scored 31 goals so far, the former Dortmund Ciro Immobile has already scored 34 goals after his three-pack in the 5: 1 (1: 1) of the fourth place in the table Lazio Rome at Hellas Verona - as many as Robert Lewandowski contributed to the title win of FC Bayern.
