In August, the next title chance awaits the "Old Lady" of Italian football.
Juventus is in the Champions League round of 16, but has to make up a 0 – 1 first leg against Olympique Lyon on 7 August to reach the final tournament in Lisbon.
In the next knockout round Real would wait Madrid or Manchester City as opponents.
Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all the punishments and court rulings threatened, motorists continue to accelerate countless illegal races on the Baden-Württemberg roads: last year and the first four months of this year, the police have already registered more than 250 illegal car races in the southwest.
Although there are no comparative figures for the years before, the speedsters are increasingly doing work to the judicial authorities: a total of 155 investigations were conducted at the prosecutors' offices between Konstanz and Mannheim in 2018 for illegal races, one year later there were already 252 and in the current year by the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the response of the Ministry of the Interior to a request from the Landtag SPD.
In most cases, the drivers spontaneously competed against each other or fled the police - this is also indicated as an illegal race.
German men between the ages of 18 and 60 sat at the wheel.
113 fines - 15 imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the speedsters caught and also asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines have been imposed since 2018 and 15 prison sentences have been imposed.
However, there is no evidence that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, other drivers reacted more sensitively than before because of the many tragic accidents and processes of past years and reported more frequently, said a ministerial spokesman.
Especially popular with racers is the highway 8. Again and again, motorists there slow down the traffic to get space and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen riders were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 riders on the A8 at Merklingen.
A81 is most popular "race track"
On the A81, the police register even more races than on any other motorway.
A speed limit is used to slow down the speedsters on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and pimped up sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers dodge to the lawn to Germany because of the high penalties for too fast driving and car racing in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few distances: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on motorways," says Martin Rivoir, the transport expert of the SPD parliamentary group.
"The inhibition threshold for speedsters would be significantly higher if you were not legally on the road here and there with 200 kilometers per hour and more."
Rivoir thinks less of enlightenment or image campaigns: "Whoever disregards all rules in such a way and puts at risk not only his own life, but also the lives of other road users, is hardly achievable with reason".
ADAC calls for stronger police crackdown
On the other hand, this is not enough for the ADAC: "We assume that speedsters will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at ADAC Württemberg.
It calls for additional and also tougher controls on the affected routes.
Not infrequently, the high-speed showdown becomes more painful and momentous: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people have died nationwide in the races, including two uninvolved in a nightly crash in Stuttgart's city centre and one in Gerlingen.
In November, two young men took part in a car race.
One of the vehicles came off the road, crashed against a garden wall and remained on the side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
21 more people have been injured in the races of the past two years.
According to Interior Minister Thomas Strobl, however, stricter penalties are not necessary: "Legislative action to sanction illegal motor vehicle races harder is not seen," says the paper of the Ministry of the Interior.
