Nuremberg: Unapproved tuning meeting - police intervene, 700 vehicles and around 1100 people
Hundreds of cars and temporarily over 1000 people took part in a "tuning meeting" in the parking lot of a furniture store on Saturday night.
The police implemented their announcement to intensify control of such events.
A large tuning meeting took place on Saturday evening (25 July 2020) in Nuremberg, Südstadt.
Several hundred vehicles were involved.
According to the police of Middle Franconia, at around 10.30 p.m. the Nuremberg traffic police found an increased volume of vehicles in the area of a large parking lot in Ingolstädter Straße.
As a result, the police carried out a large number of vehicle inspections.
Only recently, the police had announced their intention to take more action against so-called autoposers.
Illegal tuning meeting in Nuremberg: Only a small part from the "scene"
The officials counted a good 700 vehicles and about 1,100 people, the police take stock.
However, only a small part of those present can be assigned to the "autoposer" and tuning scene.
Apparently, most of the relevant scene followed the appeal of the police.
On the basis of the vehicles and people on site, it can be assumed that these were mainly onlookers.
In addition, the majority of those present adhered to the applicable infection protection regulations, in particular compliance with the minimum distance and wearing a mouth-nose protection.
The on-site control measures were completed around 1: 00 a.m.
Altogether, the officials found such structural changes for 10 vehicles that the operating permit had expired.
Four of these vehicles had to be secured.
No car races
There were no illegal car races.
"The police headquarters in Middle Franconia will continue to keep an eye on what is happening and will continue to carry out increased control measures, also in connection with the emergence of onlookers," it said.
The agency News5 spoke with Jürgen Schrödinger from the towing company involved: "They all have beautiful rims, we must not scratch them," says Schrödinger.
Special tapes would be used for this.
Also because the cars are wider, the company must take care not to cause any damage.
"After all, the young people should get their cars back unscathed".
Employment Agency figures: 900 suspected cases of abuse of short-time work
Berlin - According to its own statement, the Federal Employment Agency (BA) investigates around 900 suspected cases of abuse of short-time work allowance.
"This is extremely little for more than 880,000 companies that have indicated short-time work," said Daniel Terzenbach, Member of the Executive Board responsible for the operational business of the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung.
When many companies suddenly applied for short-time work at the beginning of the Corona crisis, the BA had to react quickly.
Usually the test lasts up to three weeks.
"So much time was not available to us in this hot phase.
We will take a closer look at the final accounts.
There will certainly be some more to come.
We are not naive and have a long breath. "
Evidence of abuse would often come from the employees or trade unions concerned.
In addition, the BA uses analysis software to detect abuse patterns.
According to Terzenbach, the BA is preparing for a possible wave of insolvencies in autumn.
"Will there be significantly more insolvencies than in the previous year?
The assessments differ, but we prepare ourselves in the event of a case and already train our employees in the employment agencies for the processing of applications for insolvency money ".
The figures are still inconspicuous, said Terzenbach.
World Heritage in Potsdam: Party dissolved in the New Garden
Potsdam - On Friday evening about 40 young people celebrated a party in the New Garden.
The collection was dissolved at 8.48 p.m. by the territorial drivers of the Prussian Palaces and Gardens Foundation (SPSG), the foundation announced on PNN request.
The young people then left the park.
On Saturday evening, some young people would have played rugby in the New Garden.
The meadow was cleared by territorial drivers, said SPSG spokesman Frank Kallensee on Sunday.
There are always illegal celebrations in the parks
In the parks of the foundation, there are always accumulations in which the distance and hygiene rules COVID-19 contact regulation are not complied with.
At the end of June there was a celebration with about 300 people in the park Babelsberg, a week later about 150 people celebrated in the New Garden.
Even without corona regulation, the parks are closed at nightfall.
The storage on the meadows is prohibited according to the park regulations, there are only a few exceptions.
The foundation has been complaining for a long time that visitors are leaving more and more garbage and destroying protected biotopes.
In Berlin, meanwhile, illegal park parties have reached another dimension.
In the Hasenheide in the district of Neukölln, 5000 people celebrated an illegal techno party on the night of Sunday.
The event was dissolved by the police.
Austria: Mass tests after Corona outbreak in tourist resort
With hundreds of tests, authorities have responded to a Corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist resort of St. Wolfgang.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, according to the state authorities in Linz.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
Accordingly, many of the infected are young interns in tourism companies, but at least one holiday guest has also been tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism staff were asked to stay in their accommodation on Saturday night.
The curfew was set at 11 p.m.
"There are cancellations and cancellations there," said Hans Wieser, head of the Wolfgangsee Tourist Board, the dpa.
Some guests also left early.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist resort in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, about a third of the guests are Germans.
On Friday, the first infections became public.
The head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended on Saturday the behavior of the interns, who had celebrated in several restaurants and could have become infected there.
"We all liked to do that in our youth," he told the radio station Ö1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The Tourist Board launched an information campaign to raise young employees' awareness of the dangers of COVID-19.
From Saturday, hundreds of employees, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
In addition, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang from 15 July were contacted.
The outbreak evokes memories of the Austrian ski and party town of Ischgl in Tyrol, which was a centre of Corona spread throughout Europe in the early stages of the pandemic.
In Austria, more than 1500 people are currently infected with the virus.
The focus of the new infections is Vienna and Upper Austria.
