North Korea unlocks border town after Corona suspected case
North Korea has so far seen its own measures to ward off the coronavirus as a "brilliant success".
Now the country is reporting a suspicion for the first time.
Because of a first official Corona suspicion in the country, North Korea has completely sealed off a big city for fear of disaster.
Despite the strictest epidemiological defenses in the past six months, "the malignant virus may have been introduced into the country," the state media reported.
The state of emergency was imposed on the region around the border town of Kaesong.
The communist leadership proclaimed the highest alert level.
If the suspicion is confirmed, it would be the first official infection case with Sars-CoV-2 in the isolated country.
North Korea had not yet registered a single infection and described its defensive measures as a "brilliant success".
The information was doubted abroad.
The symptoms of the disease were reportedly found in a "runaway" who illegally crossed the military demarcation line between South and North Korea on July 19.
The person left for South Korea three years ago and has now returned across the border.
For the border crossing within the four-kilometre wide and largely mined military buffer zone, there was initially no confirmation from South Korea.
According to reports by the national news agency Yonhap, however, South Korea's military admitted the possibility of an illegal border crossing to North Korea as high.
There were investigations into some people.
North Korea claimed on Saturday, on suspicion of an emergency meeting of the Labour Party's Politburo chaired by leader Kim Jong Un.
The "dangerous situation in Kaesong could trigger a deadly and destructive catastrophe."
Kim had already ordered on Friday as a preventive measure to "completely block Kaesong and isolate every district and region from others," it continued.
The person concerned, as well as all the people in Kaesong who had had contact with her, were quarantined.
The central military commission of the party should therefore investigate the "outbreak" as well as the behavior of the responsible military unit and, if necessary, impose severe punishment.
It is estimated that about 300,000 people live in Kaesong.
