Hurricane "Hanna" reaches Texas: Help made more difficult by Corona
Washington - The first hurricane of this year's season over the Atlantic has landed in Texas.
Life-threatening floods, strong winds and heavy rainfall now threatened parts of the US state, according to the National Hurricane Center of the US climate authority NOAA on the night of Sunday (local time).
Governor Greg Abbott declared a state of emergency for many districts.
According to the US media, the corona pandemic rampant in Texas complicates the work of the helpers.
Evacuees called for caution
"Every hurricane is a huge challenge," Abbott said, according to the Houston Chronicle.
Facing the hurricane in Texas, he added, "This challenge is complicated and exacerbated considering sweeping through an area that is the state's most affected by COVID-19."
According to Johns Hopkins University, around 5,000 people have died in Texas alone as a result of the Corona pandemic.
Abbott called on people to leave their homes to be careful.
They should not disregard practices "to which we have become accustomed", such as wearing masks, the governor said, according to CBS.
It is important that everyone kept their distance.
Therefore, hotel rooms were also provided in some places.
In addition, emergency shelters on Corona should be tested.
Initially, only the coastal town of Port Mansfield was reported.
Storm warning withdrawn
With wind speeds of up to 150 kilometers per hour, "Hanna" was hit on land on the island of Padre Island just off the Texas coast.
The tropical storm had previously been upgraded to the lowest level one hurricane.
For the coastal section from Port Mansfield to Sargent, a storm surge warning was issued and later withdrawn.
Authorities expected a weakening, while "Hanna" moved inland and headed for northeastern Mexico.
"Douglas" moves towards Hawaii
In the Pacific, Hurricane Douglas headed for Hawaii at winds of around 150 kilometres per hour on the night of Sunday.
However, the hurricane center expected it to weaken further.
According to the forecast, it should be near the largest islands of Hawaii on Sunday (local time) - then as a storm just below the hurricane threshold.
Over the Atlantic Ocean, NOAA expected an above-average hurricane season this year, according to a May forecast.
The authorities had declared that up to ten hurricanes could be expected from June to the end of November, of which up to six could be very strong cyclones.
On average, there are six hurricanes per year over the Atlantic, three of which develop into storms of great strength.
In view of available climate data and the higher water temperature in the Atlantic and Caribbean, the probability of a normal season was only 30 percent, that of a below-average even only ten percent, it was said at the time.
US President Donald Trump wrote on Twitter that his administration was watching the storms closely and was in contact with the states concerned.
