Formula 1 needs a special rule to select its world champion
Since it is not possible to drive on the required number of continents, the FIA must improvise to award the World Championship titles.
All American races were cancelled.
Race calendar is becoming more and more concrete
The race calendar of the current Formula One season continues to take shape.
In addition to the ten confirmed Grand Prix, three more race tracks were added during the week.
In October, the Nürburgring in Germany and Portimão in Portugal will be driven.
On the first of November, Lewis Hamilton and Co. will compete for World Championship points at the traditional Italian race track in Imola.
According to the current level, the 2020 race calendar thus comprises 13 races.
"We are pleased to continue to make great progress in completing our plans for the 2020 season," said Formula One boss Chase Carey.
A total of 15 to 18 races in the premier class of motorsport are to be completed in this extraordinary season.
Formula 1 wants to complete its season in Asia.
The final race calendar will be fixed and published in the coming weeks.
Before the already officially targeted races in Bahrain and Abu Dhabi in December, media reports that performances in Vietnam and Malaysia could still take place at the end of November.
Regulations require races on three continents
However, the regulations of Formula 1 require at least races on three continents for the award of the World Championship.
Even if, as currently planned, only two continents are driven, there should be a world champion.
With the help of a special rule, the FIA wants to award the titles because of the coronavirus pandemic, citing "extraordinary circumstances".
The traditional start to the season in Australia in March had to be cancelled at short notice due to the looming corona crisis.
A return to the continent later this year is not an issue.
In addition, Formula 1 will not be a guest in America this year.
Cancellation encounters criticism in Brazil
Due to the tense corona situation, the races will not take place in Canada, the USA, Mexico and Brazil.
"We look forward to being with them again next season," Carey said.
The rejection of the America races was met with criticism, especially in Brazil: "The rejection was not surprising for us, but we cannot accept the reasons for it," said Tamas Rohonyi, promoter of the Grand Prix in São Paulo.
For example, the number of infections in the São Paulo area is significantly lower than in other regions of Brazil.
The concerns of some teams not to drive in Brazil would also justify no refusal.
One is prepared for the required security measures.
Greta Thunberg: Evil eye against Donald Trump went around the world
Greta Thunberg talked about her meeting with US President Donald Trump.
Greta Thunberg was a guest on Stephen Colbert's well-known latenight show via video and revealed in an interview what she had in mind when she met Donald Trump.
Klimaatkivistin Greta Thunberg was a guest in a popular US latenight show via video.
Among other things, she told about her fight against the powerful of the world.
The teenager also talked about her famous "evil eye" when she met Donald Trump.
New York City - Over the past two years, climate activist Greta Thunberg has attracted attention with her tireless commitment to the Fridays For Future movement.
Now she spoke in a well-known latenight show about her plans in the future as well as her meeting with US President Donald Trump at last year's UN climate summit.
Latenight presenter Stephen Colbert welcomed 17-year-old Thunberg to your show on Tuesday and conducted a longer interview with the Swede.
She spoke not only about her fight against climate change, but also about her conflict with the powerful of the world.
"There are some things that surprised me," she said.
"How far people go to steer the focus away from the climate crisis," she said.
"Everything from organized hate campaigns to threats just because a group of children take to the streets" she experienced.
Heads of state and leading politicians who mock them on social media or even try to silence them find them "funny" because they show the reactions "because they have no other answer".
It became particularly interesting at the end of the interview, when Greta Thunberg was approached about a well-known scene in which she gave US President Trump a bitter look.
At the 2019 UN Climate Summit in New York, for which the nude woman sailed across the Atlantic, her expressive gaze was captured by the cameras and has since been seen by countless people on the Internet.
The short clip resulted in a GIF, an animated image that ultimately became one of the most commonly used images for Trump opponents.
But what did the 17-year-old think about the US president at this moment?
